DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain examines the temporal dimension of philanthropic decision-making,
focusing on whether to donate now or invest for larger future donations. The
literature addresses three interconnected questions: (1) the normative status
of pure time preference in ethics and public policy, (2) the practical
parameters affecting "give now versus later" decisions (investment returns,
cause timing, future uncertainty), and (3) the ethical implications of
endowments and patient philanthropy strategies.

The debate over pure time preference has roots in foundational work by Broome,
Parfit, and others who argued that discounting future well-being merely
because it occurs in the future is ethically indefensible. Recent work
(Lowry & Peterson, Mogensen, Beard & Kaczmarek) has challenged this consensus,
arguing for circumstances where time preference may be rational or justified.
The climate economics literature (Stern, Groom et al.) demonstrates the
practical stakes of these debates through social discount rate controversies.

The "give now versus later" question has gained prominence through effective
altruism discussions. MacAskill's analysis identifies key parameters: expected
investment returns, the rate of diminishing marginal utility of money donated
to a cause, correlation between investment returns and cause importance, and
existential risk. Cordelli and Reich examine the intergenerational justice
implications of philanthropic timing, particularly regarding endowments that
defer giving to benefit future generations. Core and Donaldson introduce the
proximity preference framework for understanding charitable allocation across
both distance and time.

Recent work on impact investing (Harris) and venture philanthropy suggests
that the choice is not binary—patient investors may hold mission-correlated
assets that provide both financial returns and strategic value for future
giving opportunities.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain directly addresses whether asset-based utilitarian giving norms
should incorporate deferred donation strategies. If utilitarian obligations
permit or require investing assets to maximize total donations over time, this
has implications for: (1) whether asset thresholds should trigger immediate
liquidation and donation, (2) how to weigh present need against potentially
larger future donations, and (3) whether patient philanthropy is consistent
with utilitarian urgency to reduce suffering.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The literature lacks direct engagement with how asset-based versus income-based
giving norms interact with temporal donation strategies. There is limited
empirical work on how actual donors navigate give-now-versus-later tradeoffs
across different wealth levels. The role of liquidity constraints and
consumption smoothing in optimal giving timing deserves more attention.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
When synthesizing, distinguish between: (1) pure philosophical arguments about
time preference, (2) empirical parameters in climate/public economics that
inform social discount rates, (3) practical EA frameworks for individual donor
decisions, and (4) institutional questions about endowments and foundations.
The interaction between time-discounting and asset-versus-income norms may
reveal whether asset-based obligations create pressure toward deferred giving
that income-based norms avoid.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Anti-discounting consensus (Broome, Parfit, Rawls): 7 papers - Pure time
  preference is ethically indefensible; future well-being should not be
  discounted merely due to temporal location
- Qualified defense of time preference (Lowry & Peterson, Mogensen): 3 papers -
  Some forms of time preference may be rational or justified by partiality
- Give-now advocates: 3 papers - Uncertainty, urgency, and risk of value drift
  favor immediate giving
- Patient philanthropy: 5 papers - Investment, strategic timing, and
  mission-correlated assets can justify deferred giving
====================================================================
