  volume = {84},
  pages = {47--82},
  doi = {10.1093/aristotelian/84.1.47},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Parfit argues that bias toward the near—preferring benefits
  merely because they are temporally nearer—is rationally indefensible,
  analogous to preferring one's future Tuesday-self over one's future
  Wednesday-self. He distinguishes this from the rational preference for
  earlier over later painful experiences (due to relief) and argues that the
  former is a cognitive bias we should reject. This argument extends to the
  intergenerational case, suggesting that temporal location alone cannot
  justify differential concern.

  RELEVANCE: Parfit's argument against pure time preference provides the
  philosophical foundation for much of the anti-discounting position in
  philanthropy timing debates. If his argument succeeds, then giving now cannot
  be justified merely because present needs are temporally nearer—it must be
  defended on grounds of urgency, uncertainty, or strategic considerations. For
  asset-based norms, this supports evaluating investment strategies on
  consequentialist grounds rather than temporal proximity.

  POSITION: Classic philosophical argument against pure time preference;
  foundational for anti-discounting view.
  },
